
🛠️ System Design Complete Syllabus1. 
Fundamentals & Core MetricsFunctional vs Non-Functional Requirements: 
Defining what the system does vs how well it performs (security, scalability, 
reliability).System Metrics: In-depth understanding of Latency, Throughput, Availability,
and Bandwidth.Back-of-the-envelope Estimation: Estimating data size, storage requirements, network bandwidth, and memory 
allocation.Scalability: Vertical scaling (Scale-up) vs Horizontal scaling (Scale-out).System Theorems: CAP Theorem 
(Consistency, Availability, Partition Tolerance) 
and PACELC Theorem.High Availability Availability Metrics: 
Measuring system uptime using "9s" (e.g., 99.9% vs 99.999%).2. High-Level Design (HLD) 
& InfrastructureLoad Balancing: Layer 4 vs Layer 7 
load balancers, DNS routing, 
and Consistent Hashing algorithms.Caching: In-memory caching (Redis/Memcached), cache eviction policies (LRU, LF
U, FIFO), and strategies (Cache-Aside, Write-Through, Write-Behind).CDN & Proxies: Forward proxies, Reverse proxies, and 
Content Delivery Networks (Push vs Pull CDNs).API Gateways: Centralized request routing, authentication, rate limiting, 

and request transformation.Architecture Styles: Monolithic vs Microservices, Serverless, and Event-Driven Architectures.3. 
Storage & DatabasesSQL vs NoSQL: Schema design, normalization, 
ACID properties vs BASE properties, and data integrity.NoSQL Typology: Key-Value stores (DynamoDB), Document databases (MongoDB), 
Column-family (Cassandra), and Graph databases (Neo4j).Database Scaling: Database sharding (Horizontal partitioning), Replication (Master-Slave/Multi-Master), and Federation.Advanced Storage: Object storage (AWS S3) for unstructured media, Block storage, and File storage systems.4. Distributed Communication & MessagingProtocols: Deep dive into REST APIs, GraphQL, gRPC (Protocol Buffers), WebSockets, and Server-Sent Events (SSE).Asynchronous Messaging: Message Queues (RabbitMQ), Pub/Sub systems (Apache Kafka), and dead-letter queues.Service Discovery & Registry: Tools and techniques like Consul, ZooKeeper, or Eureka to manage dynamic microservice locations.5. Low-Level Design (LLD) / Object-Oriented DesignObject-Oriented Programming (OOP): Core pillars—Encapsulation, Polymorphism, Abstraction, and Inheritance.SOLID Principles: Single Responsibility, Open/Closed, Liskov Substitution, Interface Segregation, and Dependency Inversion.Design Patterns:Creational: Singleton, Factory, Abstract Factory, Builder.Structural: Adapter, Decorator, Facade, Proxy.Behavioral: Observer, Strategy, Command, State.UML & Diagrams: Class diagrams, Sequence diagrams, State machine diagrams, and Use-case mapping.Concurrency: Multi-threading, Locks (Optimistic vs Pessimistic), Semaphores, Thread pools, and Deadlock prevention.6. System Resiliency, Security, & ObservabilityResiliency Patterns: Circuit Breaker pattern, Retries with exponential backoff, Jitter, and Bulkhead.Rate Limiting: Algorithms like Token Bucket, Leaky Bucket, Fixed Window Counter, and Sliding Window Log.Security: OAuth 2.0, JWT (JSON Web Tokens), TLS/SSL encryption, data hashing, and DDoS mitigation.Observability: Centralized logging (ELK stack), Metrics collection (Prometheus/Grafana), and Distributed Tracing (Jaeger/Zipkin).7. Real-World Case StudiesSocial Media Platforms: Twitter (Timeline generation and fan-out), Instagram (Image upload & feed).Streaming Services: YouTube/Netflix (Video transcoding, adaptive bitrate streaming, low-latency delivery).Ride-Hailing & Maps: Uber/Lyft (Geospatial indexing using quad-trees/H3, dynamic pricing, location tracking).E-Commerce: Amazon (Flash sales, inventory management, shopping cart state).Chat Applications: WhatsApp/Slack (Real-time message routing, connection management, message status tracking).

